The bubbling boundary 

As another example we turn to the spacetime formed by replacing the flat part of the metric of  in Poincare
coordinates with the double analytically continued Schwarzschild bubble of nothing found in. The metric is
 
Note in this section we have changed notation slightly,  () now represents the radial variable in the bulk, and  the radial
variable on the boundary. The radial variable on the boundary, , is restricted to . In order for the spacetime to be regular at
 we require  to be periodic with period , as in the standard Euclidean black hold background, while  has the
normal  periodicity. This spacetime has a mild curvature singularity at the horizon, due to the square of the Riemann tensor
diverging there. This singularity is similar to the one found in the AdS-black string solution. It has recently been
debated whether an instability in the black string case leads to a resolution of the singularity by the black string pinching off to form a
cigar or pancake like shape. In our case, the possible instability will be different, as our time and angular
coordinates are different, hence the possible mode will not  simply be an analytic continuation of the black string mode. In addition,
because the space actually ends at the bubble, proper boundary conditions must be imposed which will be different from the black string
case. The stability and endpoint of this background is an interesting problem in its own right. Here, we merely point it out since our main
interest is to use it as a simple example.


